All Implemented Interfaces:
Classifier<String,Integer>, HasAdditionalMemory, ProcessingSort<String>, Sort<String>, AutoCloseable
public class MSDStringSort extends SortWithHelperAndAdditionalMemory<String>
Implements the MSD (Most-Significant-Digit) String Sort algorithm for sorting an array of strings. The algorithm recursively partitions strings based on the current character (digit) being evaluated, until the entire array is sorted.

    • MSDStringSort

      public MSDStringSort(CodePointMapper mapper, String description, int N, Config config, int nRuns)
      Constructs an MSDStringSort object for sorting strings using Most-Significant-Digit (MSD) radix sort.
      Parameters:
      mapper - the CodePointMapper used to interpret and map the characters of the strings.
      description - a description of the sorting process or context.
      N - the maximum number of characters in any string to consider during sorting.
      config - the Config object containing configuration settings for the sort.
      nRuns - the number of runs or iterations to be used for any specific task within the sorting process.

      public void close()
      Closes the MSDStringSort instance, ensuring that any associated resources are properly released.

      If the helper is available (as indicated by the closeHelper field), its close method is called to release any resources held by the helper. Then, the superclass's close method is invoked to perform additional cleanup, which may include releasing memory or logging relevant information about the object.

      This method is designed to ensure all resources used by the object, including helper instances and other resources managed by the parent class, are safely and effectively released.
